"{\"lesson_json\":\"{\\n  \\\"id\\\": \\\"naming-conventions\\\",\\n  \\\"title\\\": \\\"Naming Conventions\\\",\\n  \\\"description\\\": \\\"Choose appropriate variable names and follow Python naming conventions\\\",\\n  \\\"template\\\": \\\"isActive = False\\\\na = 10\\\\nb = 'Hello'\\\\nx = True\\\\n\\\",\\n  \\\"solution\\\": \\\"is_active = False\\\\nage = 10\\\\ngreeting = 'Hello'\\\\nis_active = True\\\\n\\\",\\n  \\\"entrypoint\\\": \\\"\\\",\\n  \\\"inputs\\\": {},\\n  \\\"time\\\": 1,\\n  \\\"mode\\\": \\\"line\\\"\\n}\",\"lesson_markdown\":\"# Naming Conventions\\n\\nWelcome to the world of PythonQuest! In this lesson, you will learn about naming conventions and how to choose appropriate variable names in Python.\\n\\n## Choosing Variable Names\\n\\nNaming conventions are a set of guidelines that developers follow to make their code more readable and maintainable. In Python, variables are written in snake case, where words are separated by underscores.\\n\\nWhen writing a variable name, make sure to be descriptive and use meaningful words. Let's take a look at some examples:\\n\\n### Bad Naming\\n```python\\nisActive = False # not snake case\\na = 10\\nb = 'Hello'\\nx = True\\n```\\n\\n### Good Naming\\n```python\\nis_active = False\\nage = 10\\ngreeting = 'Hello'\\nis_active = True\\n```\\n\\nChoose variable names that accurately represent the data they hold and follow the Python naming conventions.\\n\",\"lesson_typescript\":\"import { useEffect } from 'react';\\n\\nimport { useLessonStore } from '@/store/lessonStore';\\nimport { useVariablesDefined } from '@/utils/taskChecks';\\n\\nimport content from './naming-conventions.md?raw';\\n\\nexport function useNamingConventions(lessonId: string) {\\n  // Add lesson-specific logic here\\n  const { startLesson, completeTask, currentTask } = useLessonStore();\\n  const variablesDefined = useVariablesDefined({\\n    is_active: true,\\n    age: 10,\\n    greeting: 'Hello',\\n  });\\n\\n  useEffect(() => {\\n    if (lessonId !== 'naming-conventions') return;\\n    // Start the lesson\\n    startLesson(lessonId, content, []);\\n  }, [lessonId, startLesson]);\\n\\n  // Check if the variables are defined\\n  useEffect(() => {\\n    if (variablesDefined) {\\n      completeTask();\\n    }\\n  }, [variablesDefined, completeTask]);\\n}\\n\"}"